<article>
    <h1>Nowhere to go? You can still cruise or fly</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201220/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-20"><time>2020-12-20</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Clara Lock</span>
    </section>

    <p>Never mind that there are no ports of call.</p>
    <p>You can still watch world-class live per­for­mances, dine on in­ter­na­tional cui­sine, surf ar­ti­fi­cial waves on the FlowRider and even drive bumper cars on a cruise to nowhere, re­launched last month as part of a pi­lot for safe cruis­ing.</p>
    <p>Two ships, Gent­ing Cruise Lines’ World Dream and Royal Caribbean In­ter­na­tional’s Quan­tum of the Seas, are cur­rently al­lowed to op­er­ate at 50 per cent ca­pac­ity and have proven pop­u­lar among Sin­ga­pore res­i­dents crav­ing a much­needed get­away.</p>
    <p>Those wor­ried about the coro­n­avirus may be re­as­sured by rig­or­ous safety rules.</p>
    <p>Pas­sen­gers have to take a manda­tory swab test be­fore board­ing and keep their masks on when not din­ing. Self-ser­vice buf­fets have been sus­pended. And fewer guests means more pri­vacy – al­ways wel­come re­gard­less of size of ship.</p>
    <p>Miles above, air­lines have launched flights to nowhere, such as EVA Air’s moon gaz­ing flight, de­signed for the Mid-Au­tumn Fes­ti­val in Oc­to­ber when the moon was full and bright. The three-hour flight took off and landed from Taoyuan In­ter­na­tional Air­port in Tai­wan.</p>
    <p>In­stead of a small tur­bo­prop plane that Tai­wan’s air­lines usu­ally de­ploy for do­mes­tic flights, pas­sen­gers flew on a Boe­ing 787 Dream­liner built for ul­tra-long-haul jour­neys, pay­ing NT$5,888 (S$278) for an econ­omy-class ticket.</p>
    <p>Sin­ga­pore Air­lines flirted with a sim­i­lar idea, but dropped the plan af­ter a re­view and mar­ket study, cit­ing fac­tors such as en­vi­ron­men­tal im­pli­ca­tions and fi­nan­cial vi­a­bil­ity. En­vi­ron­men­tal groups had raised con­cerns over in­creased car­bon emis­sions from flights to nowhere.</p>

